  <notes id="bio3">
    <title>Author Biographies</title>
    <p><bold>Ken Nakatsu</bold> is an undergraduate student at Emory University, focusing on Applied Mathematics and Statistics. His research interest lies in utilizing computer science and mathematics to enhance the understanding of small RNA sequencing data. He aims to apply statistics and machine learning for a better understanding of rare diseases through transcriptomics and data mining.</p>
    <sec sec-type="author-bio" id="sec26">
      <p><bold>Mayumi Jijiwa</bold>, is a Physician Scientist and Post-Doctoral researcher at the John A. Burns School of Medicine, University of Hawaii at Manoa, Department of Quantitative Health Science. Her research interests include liquid biopsy for cancer diagnostics and studying Neural Crest derived cancers. She has contributed to several publications, notably in areas like cerebellar hypoplasia, lipid molecules in cancer diagnosis, and spermatogonial stem cell self-renewal.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec sec-type="author-bio" id="sec27">
      <p><bold>Vedbar Khadka</bold> is an Assistant Professor and Bioinformatician at the John A. Burns School of Medicine, University of Hawaii at Manoa, Department of Quantitative Health Science. His work includes a global metagenomic map of urban microbiomes, cancer cell-produced collagens in tumor budding, and microRNA panels for early-stage breast cancer detection. His publications also explore diverse topics like gene expression in eggshell biomineralization and the role of selenoprotein in cancer.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec sec-type="author-bio" id="sec28">
      <p><bold>Masaki Nasu</bold> is a Post-Doctoral Researcher at the John A. Burns School of Medicine, University of Hawaii at Manoa, Department of Quantitative Health Science. His research encompasses a broad range of topics, including the susceptibility to asbestos and mesothelioma, lipid species as diagnostic markers for prostate and breast cancer, and the genetic predisposition to cancer syndromes.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec sec-type="author-bio" id="sec28a">
      <p><bold>Youping Deng</bold>, Principal Investigator, is a Full Member of the Cancer Biology Program at the University of Hawaiʻi Cancer Center and also serves as the Co-Director of the Genomics and Bioinformatics Shared Resource. His research, based in the Department of Quantitative Health Sciences at the John A. Burns School of Medicine, spans several areas including computational method development, identification of non-invasive biomarkers for cancer detection, characterization of biomarkers for clinical outcomes, and integrative data analysis of “omics” and clinical data for precision medicine.</p>
    </sec>
  </notes>
