  <sec id="sec1">
    <title>INTRODUCTION</title>
    <p>Evidence of transfer RNA (tRNA) fragmentation has been reported since at least 1969 [<xref rid="ref1" ref-type="bibr">1</xref>]. However, it was only in the last few decades that the functional roles of these fragments in relation to disease was revealed [<xref rid="ref2" ref-type="bibr">2–4</xref>]. Fragmentation of other small RNAs (sRNAs) such as small nucleolar RNAs (snoRNAs) and ribosomal RNAs (rRNAs) have also been reported, majority of which are derived from the 3’ and 5’ ends of the primary transcript [<xref rid="ref5" ref-type="bibr">5</xref>]. While much of the sRNA fragment literature has been focused on tRNA-derived fragments, there is rising evidence that fragments derived from other biotypes of sRNAs have a mechanistic role in disease and human health by influencing translation and alternative splicing [<xref rid="ref6" ref-type="bibr">6–8</xref>]. Reanalysis of Photoactivatable-Ribonucleoside-Enhanced Cross linking and Immunoprecipitation (PAR-CLIP) sequencing data sets have revealed that fragments derived from snoRNAs and rRNAs associate with Argonaute proteins, a component of the RNA-induced silencing complex which facilitates RNA interference [<xref rid="ref9" ref-type="bibr">9–11</xref>]. Furthermore, fragmentation of sRNAs has been found to occur in eukaryotes besides humans, including mice, fruit flies and chickens [<xref rid="ref12" ref-type="bibr">12</xref>]. Thus, a pipeline that can easily call fragments is needed to understand why fragmentation is conserved, which may provide insights into their function.</p>
    <p>One of the shortcomings in non-tRNA sRNA-fragment literature is that it does not have curated annotations such as MINTbase [<xref rid="ref13" ref-type="bibr">13</xref>]. sRNAfrag seeks to be a step toward generating such annotations. MINTbase was generated using the MINTmap algorithm which creates a lookup table for every possible fragment that can be derived from tRNAs, assigning each to a unique sequence-based license plate allowing IDs to be reproduced easily [<xref rid="ref14" ref-type="bibr">14</xref>]. One of the downsides of this method, which we sought to address, is that generating lookup tables from longer sRNAs such as rRNAs would result in a file that ranges in the hundreds of gigabytes. Finally, the authors of the MINTmap algorithm recognized the importance of validating potential fragments before claiming their existence by mapping them to other potential sRNAs.</p>
    <p>Other tools exist to analyze the fragmentation of sRNAs that are not tRNAs. The FlaiMapper algorithm detects peaks within BAM files and can accurately reconstruct start and end loci for mature micro RNAs (miRNAs) [<xref rid="ref15" ref-type="bibr">15</xref>]. However, since BAM files are used as an input, users must make decisions while processing raw reads which can lead to different results and introduced biases dependent upon factors such as the assignment of multi-mapping reads or mismatch parameters [<xref rid="ref16" ref-type="bibr">16</xref>]. sRNAs including rRNAs, small nuclear (snRNAs), snoRNAs and tRNAs also often have many isoforms in eukaryotic genomes that fragments align to [<xref rid="ref17" ref-type="bibr">17–20</xref>]. Thus, the multi-mapping problem must at least be addressed.</p>
    <p>The authors behind SURFr (Short Uncharacterized RNA Finder) present a new alignment algorithm and use continuous wavelet transformation to identify peaks [<xref rid="ref21" ref-type="bibr">21</xref>]. While it represents a new and interesting way to handle fragments, their web portal could not be accessed as of 16 June 2023.</p>
    <p>Notably, sRNA sequencing libraries do not undergo fragmentation (typical in standard RNA-seq) and are instead size selected through gel or bead based protocols. [<xref rid="ref22" ref-type="bibr">22</xref>]. This is useful to keep in mind when designing computational pipelines and was used in Tang et. al’s. [<xref rid="ref23" ref-type="bibr">23</xref>] Anchor Alignment-based Small RNA Annotation (AASRA) method to justify the addition of anchors to the 3’ and 5’ ends of sRNA sequencing reads to discriminate between similar sRNAs. With this in mind, we assume throughout this paper that if a portion of a longer sRNA (100–200nt) has supporting reads, we count it as a fragment of that longer sRNA as many others have done [<xref rid="ref5" ref-type="bibr">5–10</xref>].</p>
    <p>With this idea in mind, we sought to combine elements from these different methods and pipelines to create sRNAfrag, a pipeline to analyze sRNA fragmentation not only from sRNA sequencing runs but also between them. This pipeline integrates a vast array of functionalities, including count normalization, distribution analysis, cross-database annotation, motif analysis and relative expression profiling, complemented by a suite of conversion tools, annotation file descriptors and General Transfer Format (GTF) generation and modification utilities. Furthermore, sRNAfrag is designed to be a collaborative and evolving platform: any user can contribute to its development through simple pull requests, thereby enhancing its capabilities and fostering a community-driven approach. This open collaboration model not only expands the tool’s utility but also significantly contributes to improving reproducibility and innovation in the field of sRNA analysis. The pipeline requires only raw reads, an annotation file and a reference genome to run, leaving only the demultiplexing of samples and library preparation to the user.</p>
  </sec>
  <sec id="sec2">
    <title>RESULTS</title>
    <sec id="sec2a">
      <title>sRNAfrag effectively calls peaks and has a wide range of potential applications in srna research</title>
      <p>Here, we seek to demonstrate that sRNAfrag is able to accurately quantify sRNA fragment counts and identify their potential start and end cleavage sites. We aim to establish that sRNAfrag’s performance is comparable with, if not better than, other existing tools in this field. To accomplish this, we validated the accuracy of our tool’s predicted cleavage loci using mature miRNA start and end positions from MiRbase, treating pre-miRNAs as the progenitors of miRNAs. In terms of obtaining the start and end loci of cleavage, sRNAfrag’s performance was benchmarked against the Flaimapper pipeline. Because the computational task of peak detection is fairly trivial, we deemed one pipeline for comparison to be sufficient. We also compared the sRNA counts obtained from sRNAfrag with those from the AASRA pipeline.</p>
      <p>sRNAfrag had 597 pre-miRNAs with supporting fragments after filtering compared with the 642 that FlaiMapper obtained. The discrepancy between the two pipelines exist because sRNAfrag deals with multi-mapping by dividing the number of associated counts by the number of loci it could have originated from. Thus, filtering based on counts is more strict in sRNAfrag. Of these pre-miRNAs, sRNAfrag called 94.7% and 86.5% of start and end loci within 1 bp of their true position (<xref rid="f1" ref-type="fig">Figure 1A</xref>). This is comparable with FlaiMapper which called 92.4% and 85.2% of start and end loci in our dataset with default settings [<xref rid="ref15" ref-type="bibr">15</xref>]. Notably, offsets are not a result of false peak callings. Rather, count peaks exist at positions that do not exactly match loci in miRbase as can be seen in [<xref rid="sup1" ref-type="supplementary-material">Additional Figure 1</xref>].</p>
      <fig position="float" id="f1">
        <label>Figure 1</label>
        <caption>
          <p><bold>Peak and Count Calling Performance</bold> A) Proportion of detected peaks versus offset from truth for end and start loci. B) Peak calling counts versus AASRA-generated counts. Counts are unmerged and represent the unadjusted counts for that loci. C) Merged counts after P2 Module versus AASRA-generated counts.</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="bbad515f1" position="float"/>
      </fig>
      <p>Comparing the counts used to call peaks with that of AASRA shows that sRNAfrag utilizes counts that are comparable with more standard sRNA-seq workflows during peak calling, affirming that, in our pipeline, loci-count relationships are properly preserved and used (<xref rid="f1" ref-type="fig">Figure 1B</xref>). After peaks are called, fragments are clustered together in a manner dependent upon their distance from the nearest start or end peak. After clustering, we find that the fit of the regression improves and that the slope is closer to one, indicating that counts are better resolved (<xref rid="f1" ref-type="fig">Figure 1C</xref>). We infer that the underestimation of slope (0.983) and negative intercept is partially due to the AASRA pipeline’s behavior to assign alignments that have a 1 n.t. mismatch stretching beyond the source transcript due to the anchoring feature of that pipeline. Because of this, starting positions prior to the first loci of the annotation are counted as being apart of that transcript. On the other hand, sRNAfrag does not, as a sequence preceding a transcript is not considered when generating the lookup table. We verify the performance of AASRA by benchmarking the method against a synthetic dataset whose results presented in [<xref rid="sup2" ref-type="supplementary-material">Additional Figure 2</xref>].</p>
      <p>In concluding this section, we present 12 potential use cases to answer questions documented in prior research in <xref rid="TB1" ref-type="table">Table 1</xref>. Interestingly, during our analysis, we observed a possible cell-type specificity in snoRNA fragmentation, as depicted in [<xref rid="sup3" ref-type="supplementary-material">Additional Figure 3</xref>]. These applications, each likely requiring several hours to develop and validate, underscore the utility of our toolkit in enhancing both efficiency and reproducibility in future research endeavors.</p>
