    <sec id="sec2b">
      <title>Multi-mapping events reveal potentially important conserved fragments loci</title>
      <p>The utility of sRNAfrag expands beyond the basic analyses presented in the summary report depicted in [<xref rid="sup4" ref-type="supplementary-material">Additional File 1</xref>].In the sRNA space, the multi-mapping problem poses a formidable problem. However, we decided to utilize multi-mapping reads to attempt to elucidate important loci under the hypothesis that important portions of the sRNA fragment would be conserved across evolutionary time and duplication events. We again explore miRNAs as a model. The 5’ seed sequence of miRNAs represent the functionally important portion of the molecule [<xref rid="ref24" ref-type="bibr">24</xref>]. Furthermore, miRNA families, arising from duplication events, are likely subject to evolutionary pressures to retain the same seed sequence [<xref rid="ref25" ref-type="bibr">25</xref>]. Utilizing a function packaged with sRNAfrag, we extracted the a) most commonly shared fragment(s) between source transcripts and b) most counted fragment within a cluster.</p>
      <p>The mir-30 family had four (three are depicted, with the final being 1 n.t. longer) fragments that were shared among all potential sources (<xref rid="f2" ref-type="fig">Figure 2A</xref>). Each were aligned at their 5’ ends, representing the beginning of the 5’ derived mature miRNA (hsa-miR-30c-5p) despite differing 5’ flanking sequences. With this in mind, we investigated all clusters of fragments with more than one potential source transcript. We found that the 5’ end of the most counted fragment match the most commonly shared fragment 65.9% of the time (<xref rid="f2" ref-type="fig">Figure 2B</xref>). This lays in contrast to the 3’ end which matches only 34.2% of the time, which indicates that cells may be more selective about cleavage sites proximal to the function portion of the fragment.</p>
      <fig position="float" id="f2">
        <label>Figure 2</label>
        <caption>
          <p><bold>Comparative Analysis of Fragments Involved in Multi-Mapping Events</bold> A-B) The black triangles depict the most highly expressed fragment of the source transcript. The red line depicts the most shared fragment between potential sources. Three clustered fragments shared between hsa-miR-30b/30c and one fragment shared between 12 isoforms of snoRD115 whose 5’ end is the same as the most conserved fragment is depicted. C-D) Piechart depicting the proportion of merged fragments (with more than one possible source transcript) whose most commonly shared fragment between sources has a the same 3’ or 5’ loci as the most counted transcript. The percentage of transcripts whose shared loci represent either the start or end of the source transcript is also indicated. Greater than 0 represents occurrences when the most found and counted transcript do not match.</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="bbad515f2" position="float"/>
      </fig>
      <p>We attempted to apply the same logic to a fragment derived from snoRD115 and snoRNAs to see if selectivity occurs at either the 3’ or 5’ ends, which may be indicative of functionality. The fragment in question was shared between 12 source transcripts that had slight differences in sequence at their 3’ ends (<xref rid="f2" ref-type="fig">Figure 2B</xref>). While the proposed multiple sequence alignment (MSA) appeared promising, we found that the fragmentation of snoRNAs was inherently different from miRNAs. Exploring the location of these fragmentation events showed that 27.7% of conservation events were at terminal portion of the source transcript compared with just 1.5% for miRNAs (<xref rid="f2" ref-type="fig">Figure 2D</xref>). This may indicate that snoRNA fragment functionality (assuming functionality is derived from the sequence) is either (1) maintained by cleaving the fragment in such a way that the terminal end remains constant or (2) influenced by selective conservation of specific internal sequences, rather than the terminal ends. It is crucial to note that 42.5% and 40.4% of snoRNA fragments have the most counted fragment match, the most commonly shared fragment whose 5’ and 3’ ends are conserved in the middle of the snoRNA, which may indicate that functionality is not specific to any terminal end of the snoRNA. In the future, similar assignments could allow for better understanding of fragment biogenesis in other biotypes of sRNAs. Finally, instances where the most frequently found and counted transcript do not match can be attributed to the inherent complexities of sRNA processing and the nature of multi-mapping events in sRNA sequencing.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="sec2c">
      <title>Loci level variance score holds potential biological relevance</title>
      <p>Each cluster of fragments included in the output from sRNAfrag is associated with a dictionary of loci relative to their potential source transcripts that are associated with counts. Going source by source, the main peak is marked. With this, we calculated a variance-like score for each cluster–source pair by multiplying the square of the difference between the peak loci and fragment loci by the proportion of counts a fragment makes up, providing a descriptive statistic into count spread. This was done for both the start and end loci.</p>
      <p>To investigate whether this variance-like score is biologically significant, we applied it to our cell line data with the hypothesis that different types of cells will maintain the stability of their fragments to differing degrees. Interestingly, we found that the score was specific to the biotype of sRNA (<xref rid="f3" ref-type="fig">Figure 3A-B</xref>). After zeroes were removed, a two-tailed students T-test yielded <italic toggle="yes">P</italic> &lt; 0.001 for all comparisons with snoRNA in the start and end buckets, indicating that each biotype has its own unique level of stability. We also observed that the 3’ ends of sRNAs tended to have a higher score than their 5’ counterparts. Further, 6.0%, 26.2% and 30.1% of cluster–source pairs had an start score of 0 for rRNA, snRNA and snoRNA, respectively, while their end scores were 6.3%, 23.2% and 26.2%. This indicates that, out of the three biotypes we investigated, snoRNAs are the most specific around their cleavage sites.</p>
      <fig position="float" id="f3">
        <label>Figure 3</label>
        <caption>
          <p><bold>Loci Level Variance Scores and UMAP Dimension Reduction</bold> A-B) Distribution of start and end loci-level variance scores across rRNA, snoRNA and snRNA in human samples. Zero values were omitted from the figure. C-H) UMAP dimension reduction applied to start and end scores for human cell lines with three primary classes of cells: Healthy epithelial, breast cancer and neuroblastoma.</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="bbad515f3" position="float"/>
      </fig>
      <p>Given that we observed biotype specificity in terms of fragment cleavage site stability, we sought to investigate if the variance-score is sample- or condition-specific in our cell line data. For each cluster, we obtained the sum of of all cluster–source pairs. The score matrix was subjected to uniform manifold approximation and projection (UMAP) to reduce its dimensionality. We observed that replicates derived from separate cultures of the same cell line type typically clustered together, indicating that our loci-variance is reproducible. (<xref rid="f3" ref-type="fig">Figure 3C-H</xref>). The only exception occurred with snRNA start and end scores for the SK-N-SH neuroblastoma cell line. Interestingly, we noticed the strongest clustering on the basis of cancer type in snoRNA start and end loci variance scores (<xref rid="f3" ref-type="fig">Figure 3E,H</xref>). This is noteworthy because this condition-specific level of variance around cleavage sites may impact novel diagnostics such as liquid biopsy as sequence changes may impact primer binding if RT-qPCR is used.</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="sec2d">
      <title>License plating allows conserved fragments to be detected</title>
      <p>Given that orthologous snoRNA genes are fairly common, we decided to investigate if fragments of similar sequence could also be conserved across species [<xref rid="ref26" ref-type="bibr">26</xref>]. Hamming distance calculates the number of differences between two sequences of equal length. Using this method, 1411 conservation events between two species were found with a hamming distance at most of 3, majority of which were fragments shared between M. musculus and H. sapiens (<xref rid="f4" ref-type="fig">Figure 4A</xref>).</p>
      <fig position="float" id="f4">
        <label>Figure 4</label>
        <caption>
          <p><bold>Shared snoRNA Fragments between Species</bold> Source transcripts are depicted with fragment source cluster loci highlighted in red. A) Heatmap depicting number of shared fragments between four species, M. musculus, H. sapiens, A. thaliana, and C. elegans. Diagonals are set to 0. B) Shared snoRNA fragment with hamming distance of two relative to H. sapien and M. musculus fragments in panel (C) and (D). Derived from unassigned_transcript_14429. C) H. sapiens snoRNA-derived fragment, with hamming distance of 0 relative to M. musculus fragment depicted in panel (D). Derived from SNORD15A. D) M. musculus snoRNA-derived fragment. Derived from NR_002172.1 (SNORD15A). E) Multi-sequence alignment results for the conserved 3’ fragment, from which hamming distance was calculated.</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="bbad515f4" position="float"/>
      </fig>
      <p>Out of the 1411, we chose to investigate one shared fragment (snoRD15A in humans and mouse) derived from the 3’ ends of primary transcripts in three-fourths of our chosen species. RNAfold and RNAplot was used to generate minimum free energy structures of source transcripts [<xref rid="ref27" ref-type="bibr">27</xref>]. The sRNAfrag workflow associates fragments with a cluster which has associated start and end loci. The cluster start and end are highlighted on the secondary structure, as opposed to the fragment start and end (<xref rid="f4" ref-type="fig">Figure 4B-D</xref>). The fragment derived from the C. elegans snoRNA was the most different out of the three, with a hamming distance of two (<xref rid="f4" ref-type="fig">Figure 4B</xref>). The fragments derived from snoRNAs in H. sapiens and M. musculus shared the same sequence (<xref rid="f4" ref-type="fig">Figure 4C-D</xref>). Fragments were derived from SNORD15A which is annotated for M. musculus and H. sapiens. This is a proof of concept that attempting to explore fragmentation between species may not only be fruitful, but is also made easier with sRNAfrag as its outputs can be joined and used in scripts such as the one used in this section. The MSA of the fragments is also depicted (<xref rid="f4" ref-type="fig">Figure 4E</xref>).</p>
    </sec>
    <sec id="sec2e">
      <title>sRNAfrag run time scales linearly for multiple biotypes and species</title>
      <p>We tested sRNAfrag with four different species (M. musculus, A. thaliana, C. elegans, H. sapiens) and three biotypes of sRNAs (snoRNA, snRNA, rRNA) with a maximum of one job. The amount of time that sRNAfrag takes exhibits a linear relationship with the number of fragments discovered in a manner that is mostly independent of the number of sequenced reads (<xref rid="f5" ref-type="fig">Figure 5A</xref>). For every 1000 additional unique fragments discovered, users can expect an additional 23 s of run time. Note that parallelization can increase speed of time-intensive modules such as sorting of SAM file and alignment back to reference genome. This is slower than reported times in SURFr, taking an average of 4.5 min to complete jobs [<xref rid="ref21" ref-type="bibr">21</xref>]. However, our pipeline has two important modules which we find important for varying reasons.</p>
      <fig position="float" id="f5">
        <label>Figure 5</label>
        <caption>
          <p><bold>sRNAfrag Run Time and Human Outside Map Composition</bold> A) Overall run time in minutes. B–D) The composition of out of space maps for rRNA, snRNA and snoRNA fragments in humans.</p>
        </caption>
        <graphic xlink:href="bbad515f5" position="float"/>
      </fig>
      <p>Firstly, especially large run times are observed for runs where over 10 000 are processed. This is because when the number of fragments surpasses 8000, sampling of the smallest fragments is conducted, which takes a significant amount of time on top of alignment time. We justify the importance of detecting outside maps by investigating where fragments are mapping to in our cell line dataset. We found that most reads from fragments map to piRNAs (<xref rid="f5" ref-type="fig">Figure 5B-D</xref>). Interestingly, snRNA U1 has been found to be similar to that of tandem repeat tRNA, which may explain why snRNA fragment alignments were annotated as tRNAs [<xref rid="ref28" ref-type="bibr">28</xref>]. We believe that these results indicate that outside maps should always be assessed as they are always existent.</p>
      <p>Secondly, generation of the lookup table takes a significant amount of time as it requires that sequences be sorted and queried. We originally generated a lookup table of all possible fragments. However, this led to memory issues, especially as possible fragments would range in the tens of millions (<xref rid="TB2" ref-type="table">Table 2</xref>). Furthermore, fragments that exist typically represent only a small fraction of possible sequences in nearly every species tested.</p>
